  "original_title": "\u0dbb\u0dcf\u0da2\u0dca\u200d\u0dba \u0d86\u0daf\u0dcf\u0dba\u0db8 \u0db4\u0dd6\u0dbb\u0dca\u0dc0 \u0dc0\u0dc3\u0d82\u0d9c\u0dad \u0db8\u0da7\u0dca\u0da7\u0db8\u0da7 \u0dc5\u0d9f\u0dcf \u0dc0\u0dd9\u0dba\u0dd2",
  "text_idx": {
    "en": {
      "title": "Government revenues reach pre-pandemic levels",
      "author": "unknown",
      "body_lines": [
        "Central bank data showed that government revenue had reached pre-pandemic levels, posting annual growth of 17.5 percent in the first five months of the year.",
        "In the first five months of 2021, Rs. The revenue of 630.1 billion has increased to 811.9 billion rupees in the first 5 months of 2022.",
        "The increase in tax rates and the imposition of a one-time surcharge on large companies have led to a rise in government revenue.",
        "Also, the non-tax income has increased by a large percentage from 60.8 billion rupees to 101.3 billion rupees in 2021.",
        "According to the latest government forecasts, government revenue is expected to rise to 9.1 percent of GDP this year from 8.6 percent last year, while government spending is expected to rise to 18.9 percent of GDP from 16.2 percent last year.",
        "The budget deficit is expected to narrow to 9.9 percent of GDP this year from 12.2 percent last year.",
        "After May this year, the government increased the rates of several key taxes, including income tax, VAT, telecommunications tax and betting and sports fees. In addition, a new tax of 2.5 percent has been implemented for importers, manufacturers, service providers, wholesalers and retailers."
      ],
